        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>   NGC 1977 and the Orion Nebula are both associated with the same Orion A molecular cloud complex at a distance of ~400 pc.  The sub-mm fluxes from disks similar to P2042 embedded within the Orion Nebula are used to estimate fluxes and mass limits attainable with ALMA.  Mann &amp; Williams (2010) used SMA to survey 67 disks in the Orion Nebula, detecting 42 disks with fluxes ranging from 6 to 135 mJy at 350 GHz, implying disk masses of 0.003 to 0.07 Mo (3 to 75 MJupiter). 
    For Band 7, the correlator will be configured to observe the HCN 4-3, HCO+ 4-3, CS 7-6 and CO 3-2 transitions expected to trace the disk surface.   The lines will be observed with a resolution of 977 kHz (0.85 km/s) and a total bandwidth of 1.9 GHz and a continuum band centered at 343 GHz will be observed.  These IF bands will provide a total bandwidth of nearly 8 GHz for continuum measurements and a resolution of 0.8 km/s for spectroscopy.  The basebands are centered so that in each spectral line a window of +/-100 km/s is available to trace the fastest outflow components.  
   The P2042 disk is about 2” in diameter and the spindle is about 2” long.  The ~300 AU radius gap in the disk corresponds to a maximum separation of ~0.8” from P2042.   The tradeoff between resolution and sensitivity makes 0.2” resolution in Band 7 the best option to sample the disk structure with a 1-sigma sensitivity of 3.5 mJy (~5 Jupiter masses using standard assumptions) in 2 hours.  The HST images (Figure 2) show that the disk, inner jet, and proplyd tail have structure on scales less than 2”, smaller than the maximum angular scale of in this ALMA configuration.
   A 22 MB/s data rate is requested to accommodate our 4 spectral bands of dense gas tracers and excellent sampling of the dust continuum so we can attain the best sensitivity possible with our configuration.  Dust continuum and CO are required for our primary science goals, and HCO+, HCN, and CS are likely to be detected and give useful information about disk structure and kinematics.  They are included primarily for archival value.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
