    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>A young star, Parenago 2042, in an HII region north of the Orion Nebula has a large ~500 AU protoplanetary disk with an unusually large gap (~300 AU) and drives a fast, 160 km/s jet whose launch mechanism is unknown.  A unique feature surrounds the base of the jet axis: a series of increasingly small Hα arcs extending ~ 2” from the outer disk edge.  In a modest 2 hours, high resolution 345 GHz imaging in the dust continuum and dense gas tracers will measure the stellar mass, disk mass, mass-loss rate, neutral jet velocity, and constrain the source of the disk’s large gap.  Limits will be placed on the timescale for planet formation in this disk and disk evolution in a clustered, irradiated environment – akin to the Solar birth cluster.</prp:abstract>
